{"title":"Improving Visual Prompt Tuning for Self-supervised Vision Transformers","domain":"CV","seeds":[{"problem":"Visual Prompt Tuning (VPT) underperforms with self-supervised ViTs because prompt tokens interact with all blocks uniformly, while the blocks carrying task-relevant information vary by SSL pretraining and downstream task; exhaustively choosing optimal insertion blocks is costly.","method":"Gated Prompt Tuning introduces a learnable scalar gate per ViT block that convexly combines the prompt representation before and after each block (g_l * prompt_after + (1−g_l) * prompt_before), with a single prompt set prepended once like VPT-shallow. This learns to selectively carry forward only the influence of task-relevant blocks, yielding a selective aggregation of block outputs at the last layer and enabling sample-specific, task-relevant instructions. The method keeps the backbone frozen and trains only prompts, gates, and head, outperforming VPT baselines on FGVC (e.g., MAE 73.39% vs. 72.02% VPT-deep), VTAB-1K (MoCo v3 65.80% vs. 61.22% VPT-deep), and ADE20K (MAE 38.44 mIoU vs. 37.76 VPT-deep)."},{"problem":"Prompt tuning needs stronger control over how pretrained self-attention distributes focus so that prompts can better encode task-specific instructions in SSL ViTs.","method":"Adaptive Attention Shaping adds a learnable temperature per block that rescales the attention softmax (sharpening or smoothing) to directly modulate each block’s self-attention during transfer. Combined with Gated Prompt Tuning, this further improves adaptation: attention maps shift toward more discriminative regions, and ablations show consistent gains when adding learnable temperatures on top of gating."}]}
